This paper presents a class of interval-based temporal languages for representing and reasoning about actions and plans. The use of Description Logics and the investigation of the subsumption problem suggest that this paper is likely to belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also deals with computational properties, which could place it in the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses expressivity, which could suggest it belongs to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The use of temporal logic and the investigation of decision procedures could also place it in the Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the subsumption problem, which could suggest it belongs to the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category.
